I am trying to consume the following JSONP file with angular 10.0.8 and httpclient:
[https://opendata.euskadi.eus/contenidos/ds_informes_estudios/calidad_aire_2020/es_def/adjuntos/estaciones.json](https://opendata.euskadi.eus/contenidos/ds_informes_estudios/calidad_aire_2020/es_def/adjuntos/estaciones.json)

The following is my service class:

```
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { HttpClient, HttpClientJsonpModule } from '@angular/common/http';
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { Revision } from '../models';
 
@Injectable()
export class RevisionService { 

   baseURL : string = "https://opendata.euskadi.eus/contenidos/ds_informes_estudios/calidad_aire_2020/es_def/adjuntos/estaciones.json";
 
   constructor(private http:HttpClient){}
 
   getRevision (): Observable<Revision[]> {
       return this.http.jsonp<Revision[]>(this.baseURL, 'jsoncallback');
   }

}
```
Whis is consumed by:

```
import { Component }       from '@angular/core';
import { RevisionService } from '../../../core/services/revision.service';
import { Revision }        from '../../../core/models/revision';

@Component({templateUrl: './dashboard.component.html'})

export class DashboardComponent  {

    revisions : Revision[] = [];
    errorMessage;

    constructor(private revisionService : RevisionService) {
    	this.getRevision();
    }

    public getRevision() {
     	  this.revisionService.getRevision().subscribe((jsonCallback) => {
    		this.revisions    = jsonCallback;
      	  }, (error) => {
    		this.errorMessage = error.message;
    	  }, () => {});
    }
}
```
Every time I try to make the request, I get the following error:

```
Error: JSONP injected script did not invoke callback.
    at HTMLScriptElement.onLoad (http://localhost:4200/vendor.js:9516:22)
    at ZoneDelegate.invokeTask (http://localhost:4200/polyfills.js:3586:173)
    at Object.onInvokeTask (http://localhost:4200/vendor.js:86608:25)
    at ZoneDelegate.invokeTask (http://localhost:4200/polyfills.js:3586:56)
    at Zone.runTask (http://localhost:4200/polyfills.js:3336:39)
    at ZoneTask.invokeTask [as invoke] (http://localhost:4200/polyfills.js:3681:28)
    at invokeTask (http://localhost:4200/polyfills.js:5212:12)
    at HTMLScriptElement.globalZoneAwareCallback (http://localhost:4200/polyfills.js:5243:11)
```

Looking at the URL generated by the request, I see:
`https://opendata.euskadi.eus/contenidos/ds_informes_estudios/calidad_aire_2020/es_def/adjuntos/estaciones.json?jsoncallback=ng_jsonp_callback_0`

Which doesn't look bad at all. The request is also properly executed, and the response I get is the actual file:

```
jsonCallback([ {
  "Name" : "3 DE MARZO",
  "Province" : "Araba/√Ålava",
  "Town" : "Vitoria-Gasteiz",
  "Address" : "Plaza Tres de Marzo, s/n",
  "CoordenatesXETRS89" : "527141,4365",
  "CoordenatesYETRS89" : "4744882,8893",
  "Latitude" : "42,85604797053618",
  "Longitude" : "-2,667784994714487"
}, ... ]);
```
Am I missing something here? The documentation on [angular http](https://angular.io/guide/http) mentions setting the callback function as a parameter, which I surely do. I've been banging my head against a wall for a couple weeks now to no avail.

